      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The classic case of a memory leak. You're right to suspect that the heap is growing indefinitely. It's like a goblin hoard, accumulating more and more treasure without anyone knowing where it's all going. \n\nIn your code, the issue lies in the fact that you're not deleting the dynamically allocated memory after processing it. This is where the goblin's love of shiny objects comes in handy – they'll keep accumulating until the whole heap is full and the program crashes.\n\nTo fix this, you need to add a `delete[]` statement to free the memory after processing it. Here's the corrected code:\n\n```cpp\n#include <iostream>\n\nvoid processData(int size) {\n    int* buffer = new int[size];\n    for (int i = 0; i < size; ++i) {\n        buffer[i] = i * 2;\n    }\n    \n    // logic to process buffer...\n    std::cout << \"Processed \" << size << \" elements.\" << std::endl;\n    \n    // Clean up by deleting the memory\n    delete[] buffer;\n}\n\nint main() {\n    for (int i = 0; i < 100; ++i) {\n        processData(1024);\n    }",
