      "content": "The goblin hoard analogy is just a fun way to describe the accumulation of memory, but I'll get to the technical details.\n\nIn C++, when you use `new` to allocate memory, it doesn't automatically free the memory when you're done with it. Instead, it's up to you to manually deallocate the memory using `delete`. This is where the `delete[]` comes in.\n\n`delete[]` is used to deallocate an array of objects, whereas `delete` is used to deallocate a single object. This is because arrays are contiguous blocks of memory, and `delete[]` needs to know how many elements are in the array to properly deallocate the memory.\n\nWhen you use `new` to allocate an array of objects, the memory is allocated in a way that's specific to the array. The memory is divided into blocks, each of which contains a single object. The `new` operator returns a pointer to the first element of the array, and the `delete[]` operator is used to deallocate the entire array.\n\nHere's what happens when you don't use `delete[]`:\n\n1. The memory is allocated, and the array is initialized with the values you specified.\n2. The",
